        "created_at": "2025-10-28T17:34:30.857Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Signal calls can fail on weak networks; please consider an optional adaptive-bandwidth mode or an on-device voice-to-text / text-to-voice system to preserve privacy while improving reliability.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>I was talking with my daughter on Signal ‚Äî she was in Italy, and I was in the USA. The first 30 minutes went beautifully, but then the call quality degraded sharply. We tried reconnecting on several devices and networks, but the high quality of the first 30 minutes could not be maintained.</p>\n<p>The main issue seems to be Signal‚Äôs high bandwidth requirements for voice calls. I admire Signal‚Äôs commitment to privacy and understand that keeping packets fixed-length and continuous helps prevent metadata leaks. Still, in low-bandwidth conditions, that approach can make calls unusable.</p>\n<p>I‚Äôd like Signal to consider options that could reduce voice bandwidth use while maintaining as much privacy as possible:</p>\n<p><strong>Option 1:</strong> Allow users to <em>opt out</em> of fixed, continuous voice packets when bandwidth becomes a problem. I understand this compromises some privacy, but I would rather use a ‚Äúpartially compromised‚Äù Signal than switch to an app that‚Äôs <em>always</em> compromised, such as WhatsApp.</p>\n<p><strong>Option 2:</strong> Explore a ‚Äúvoice-to-text / text-to-voice‚Äù mode where speech is converted to text locally, transmitted as encrypted text, then re-synthesized on the receiver‚Äôs device. This would keep strong security while requiring a fraction of the data. Some tone and nuance would be lost, but it‚Äôs far better than not being able to communicate at all.</p>\n<p><strong>Option 2 Enhancement:</strong> In the future, locally generated personalized voice characteristics could restore the natural sound of each speaker, preserving familiarity while keeping all processing on-device.</p>\n<p>Thank you for considering ways to make Signal voice more resilient and inclusive for users on limited networks.</p>",
